FTC Sues Adobe
--------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-06-17/adobe-s=
ued-by-us-regulators-over-subscription-cancellation-fees ) :

The US Federal Trade Commission sued Adobe Inc., alleging the software comp=
any violated consumer protection laws by making it too difficult for consum=
ers to cancel their subscriptions. Adobe pushed users toward annual subscri=
ptions to its creative software such as Photoshop without =E2=80=9Cadequate=
ly disclosing=E2=80=9D that canceling in the first year could cost hundreds=
 of dollars, the FTC said Monday in a statement. The San Jose, California-b=
ased company also designed the cancellation process to be difficult, requir=
ing navigating many online pages or transfers between customer services rep=
resentatives, the regulators said.

=E2=80=9CAdobe trapped customers into yearlong subscriptions through hidden=
 early termination fees and numerous cancellation hurdles,=E2=80=9D said Sa=
muel Levine, director of the FTC=E2=80=99s Bureau of Consumer Protection. T=
he Justice Department filed the complaint in a California federal court on =
behalf of the FTC, which enforces US consumer protection laws.

Adobe said it will challenge the FTC=E2=80=99s claim in court. =E2=80=9COur=
 priority is to always ensure our customers have a positive experience,=E2=
=80=9D Dana Rao, the company=E2=80=99s general counsel, said in a statement=
. =E2=80=9CWe are transparent with the terms and conditions of our subscrip=
tion agreements and have a simple cancellation process.=E2=80=9D

Users of Adobe products have long complained about the expense of canceling=
 a subscription. Accessing Adobe=E2=80=99s suite of apps can cost more than=
 $700 annually for individuals. Subscribers must cancel within two weeks of=
 buying a subscription to receive a full refund; otherwise, they incur a pr=
orated penalty. Some other digital services such as those from Spotify Tech=
nology SA and Netflix Inc. don=E2=80=99t charge a cancellation fee.

This isn=E2=80=99t quite right: as long as you pick the actual =E2=80=9CMon=
thly=E2=80=9D plan you can cancel whenever you want. From the FTC=E2=80=99s=
 complaint ( https://www.ftc.gov/system/files/ftc_gov/pdf/adobe_complaint.p=
df ) (these screenshots are fuzzy because they are taken directly from the =
complaint, which has fuzzy screenshots):

Adobe=E2=80=99s enrollment flows often begin with a plan selection page tha=
t presents available subscriptions and their prices, like the one illustrat=
ed below.

*Enrollment Flow Example 1:* Plan Selection Page In Creative Cloud Free Tri=
al Flow, May 2023

The element of each plan that Adobe displays most prominently is a price, w=
ith the APM plan showing the lowest dollar amount. Adobe frequently also pr=
e-selects the APM [Annual, Paid Monthly] plan as a default.

In Enrollment Flow Example 1, the bottom of each plan selection box include=
s a less prominent line of text, followed by a =E2=80=9Ctooltip=E2=80=9D ic=
on: =E2=93=98. In particular, the APM plan box states: =E2=80=9CFee applies=
 if you cancel after 14 days. =E2=93=98.=E2=80=9D

Consumers navigating the enrollment flow do not see the additional text con=
tained in the tooltip (i.e., a small pop-up text box), which is in an even =
less prominent font, unless they hover over or click the =E2=93=98 icon. Cu=
stomers using a touchscreen device (e.g., a phone or tablet) must tap the =
=E2=93=98 icon to view the tooltip. Consumers who access the =E2=93=98 icon=
 for the APM plan in this example flow reveal a tooltip that reads: =E2=80=
=9CIf you cancel after 14 days, your service will continue until the end of=
 that month=E2=80=99s billing period, and you will be charged an early term=
ination fee.=E2=80=9D

*Enrollment Flow Example 2:* APM Plan Tooltip In Creative Cloud Free Trial =
Flow, May 2023

Enrollment Flow Example 2 is a zoomed-in version of the plan selection list=
 featured on Adobe=E2=80=99s plan selection page. In this example, the tool=
tip icon is being engaged with (i.e., hovered over or clicked), revealing t=
he informational text it displays.

As Enrollment Flow Example 2 shows, a consumer who accessed the information=
 contained behind the tooltip is still not given concrete information about=
 the amount of the ETF [Early Termination Fee], how it is calculated, or th=
e subscription term, if any, to which it applies.

As Enrollment Flow Examples 1 and 2 show, the plan selection page does not =
state anywhere that the APM plan requires a one-year commitment. Consumers =
who do not access the =E2=93=98 icon are not informed that the =E2=80=9Cfee=
=E2=80=9D mentioned in the APM box in less prominent text is an ETF.

Moreover, the plan selection page, even in the text accessible only through=
 the tooltip, does not clearly explain what constitutes =E2=80=9Cearly term=
ination,=E2=80=9D i.e., that cancelling before paying for a full year of se=
rvice will result in a fee.

Finally, the plan selection page does not disclose at all the amount of the=
 fee that consumers would be charged for early cancellation.

This is the meat of the complaint, along with a section about a convoluted =
and multi-step cancellation flow. To further clarify my point above:

* =E2=80=9CAnnual, paid monthly=E2=80=9D is basically an installment plan; =
if you cancel early the termination fee is 50% of what you would pay if you=
 stayed subscribed for the full year (the total cost of which would be $659=
.88).
* =E2=80=9CAnnual, prepaid=E2=80=9D is a single lump sum payment (and the c=
heapest option at $599.88).
* =E2=80=9CMonthly=E2=80=9D is monthly; you can cancel anytime, but it is t=
he most expensive option ($989.88 for a full year).

The specific plan at issue is =E2=80=9CAnnual, paid monthly.=E2=80=9D

The Legal Question
------------------

The law that is allegedly being violated by Adobe is the Restore Online Sho=
pper=E2=80=99s Confidence Act ( https://www.congress.gov/bill/111th-congres=
s/senate-bill/3386/text ) , which states:

It shall be unlawful for any person to charge or attempt to charge any cons=
umer for any goods or services sold in a transaction effected on the Intern=
et through a negative option feature (as defined in the Federal Trade Commi=
ssion=E2=80=99s Telemarketing Sales Rule in part 310 of title 16, Code of F=
ederal Regulations), unless the person=E2=80=94

(1) provides text that clearly and conspicuously discloses all material ter=
ms of the transaction before obtaining the consumer=E2=80=99s billing infor=
mation;

(2) obtains a consumer=E2=80=99s express informed consent before charging t=
he consumer=E2=80=99s credit card, debit card, bank account, or other finan=
cial account for products or services through such transaction; and

(3) provides simple mechanisms for a consumer to stop recurring charges fro=
m being placed on the consumer=E2=80=99s credit
card, debit card, bank account, or other financial account.

A =E2=80=9Cnegative options feature=E2=80=9D is defined as ( https://www.la=
w.cornell.edu/cfr/text/16/310.2 ) :

Negative option feature means, in an offer or agreement to sell or provide =
any goods or services, a provision under which the customer=E2=80=99s silen=
ce or failure to take an affirmative action to reject goods or services or =
to cancel the agreement is interpreted by the seller as acceptance of the o=
ffer.

There are a ton of complaints online about =E2=80=9CAnnual, paid monthly=E2=
=80=9D from people who subscribed, canceled, and were shocked to be hit wit=
h that early termination fee; frankly, I have a hard time being sympathetic=
: it=E2=80=99s pretty clear on the plan selection page that only the =E2=80=
=9CMonthly=E2=80=9D option is cancellable at any time.

That noted, I do think that Adobe probably violates the law by failing to c=
learly and conspicuously disclose all material terms of the transaction; sp=
ecifically, the only way to find out the amount of the early transaction fe=
e is to click the =E2=80=9CSubscription and Cancellation Terms=E2=80=9D on =
the final page of the subscription flow (I circled the link in red because =
you wouldn=E2=80=99t be able to see it otherwise, which kind of makes the p=
oint here):

The specific cancellation terms, including the fact that the fee is 50%, is=
 at the bottom of the modal dialog that pops up when you click that link:

Beyond the fact that these terms are buried, they also aren=E2=80=99t as cl=
ear as they can be, because the actual financial commitment of $659.88 isn=
=E2=80=99t disclosed anywhere in the process. In short, the actual annual c=
ost is never disclosed (although the consumer can calculate it), and the ea=
rly termination fee is buried; that=E2=80=99s not clear and conspicuous.

The Value of Doing Right
------------------------

A decade ago Adobe transformed their business by switching the business mod=
el of their apps away from upfront pricing to a subscription model; I wrote=
 positively about the decision in 2013=E2=80=99s Adobe=E2=80=99s Subscripti=
on Model & Why Platform Owners Should Care ( https://stratechery.com/2013/a=
dobes-subscription-model-why-platform-owners-should-care/?access_token=3Dey=
JhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6I=
