TsaV9l3Sie1RSdnA ) , making the case that a subscription model was superior=
 for productivity applications because it better matched value capture from=
 producers over time to the benefits gained by consumers, and urged the app=
 stores to support subscriptions for productivity apps (which they eventual=
ly did, and now view as an important growth driver).

At the same time, my perspective is that of a business analyst; I am sympat=
hetic to the Adobe users who were used to paying once for their software, a=
nd being able to use it forever if they so chose, being forced to pay on a =
subscription basis. What I also recognize is the inherent distaste a lot of=
 people have for paying for software generally, given its zero marginal cos=
t nature; granted, there are significant costs when it comes to maintaining=
 online services, but that=E2=80=99s part of people=E2=80=99s beef with Ado=
be: they primarily want applications that run on their computer, and the ad=
dition of an online service (Creative Cloud) is galling precisely because i=
ts primary utility is enforcing that subscription model on (mostly) locally=
-run software.

Ultimately Adobe was able to get away with this because they are the standa=
rd across multiple creative industries, which creates an interesting sort o=
f two-sided network between employers and employees: employers expect emplo=
yees to be proficient in Adobe applications, and employees acquire marketab=
le skills by being proficient in Adobe applications. Both sides may get gru=
mpy about Adobe, but they also aren=E2=80=99t going to move to an alternati=
ve because the cost =E2=80=94 not in terms of software, but in missed oppor=
tunities =E2=80=94 is too high; this fact means that it is difficult for ch=
allengers to gain a foothold, particularly in terms of volume licensing dea=
ls.

I am, up to this point, still pretty sympathetic to Adobe=E2=80=99s positio=
n, and again, remember that I am a business analyst first and foremost: Ado=
be recognized the strength of their position and leveraged that into a much=
 more profitable business model, and I respect that. At the same time, I th=
ink it behooves any entity in such a position to play above the board to th=
e greatest extent possible: you are extracting maximum profits by leveragin=
g your market position, which both makes your customers unhappy and has the=
 risk of attracting regulatory scrutiny, which is exactly what happened her=
e. Adobe=E2=80=99s violation is arguably minor, but what is most irksome is=
 that it seems fairly unnecessary: just post the real costs, which the vast=
 majority of your customers are going to pay regardless.

More generally, what bothers me about this case is the moral component; I a=
ssume this entire purchase flow has been A/B tested to death, and that the =
current configuration makes the most money, at least across whatever timeli=
ne is being considered. However, did anyone at Adobe stop and consider why =
that might be? Is there any answer other than, some number of users won=E2=
=80=99t be careful enough and will buy the wrong plan, and then get hit wit=
h a large fee, which will either drive revenue on its own or convince the u=
ser to begrudgingly not cancel, driving more revenue going forward? Even le=
aving aside the long-term hit to the brand=E2=80=99s reputation, what about=
 doing the right thing?

I would, generally speaking, prefer less government regulation rather than =
more, and I think I speak for a lot of people in tech in that regard. Those=
 people in tech, though, need to appreciate the extent to which choices lik=
e this one made by Adobe invite exactly that. No, I don=E2=80=99t think thi=
s so-called =E2=80=9Cdark pattern=E2=80=9D is that dark, if you take just a=
 second or two to look at the plans on offer; yes, there seems to me to be =
far more egregious cases that break the law in question much more flagrantl=
y (like publications that make you call to cancel). However, at the end of =
the day, Adobe wasn=E2=80=99t satisfied with harvesting the natural gains f=
rom their dominant market position: they had to make money off of people sc=
rewing up too, and it=E2=80=99s hard to feel bad for them facing regulatory=
 action for not doing right by potential customers.

Zooming out more generally, I wrote above that =E2=80=9CI assume=E2=80=A6th=
e current configuration makes the most money, at least across whatever time=
line is being considered=E2=80=9D; I further assume that timeline didn=E2=
=80=99t include this lawsuit and the possible attendant fines. It almost ce=
rtainly does not consider whatever configuration of software or workflows e=
ventually displaces Adobe, fueled in part by user animosity towards practic=
es like this (and to what extent that animosity drove a regulatory response=
 to the abandoned Figma acquisition is unknown as well). Indeed, that is th=
e challenge with the long-run: it=E2=80=99s hard to measure, and thus easil=
y forgotten in metrics-driven decisions; all the more reason to have a bias=
 towards doing the right thing, the value of which is eternal.

